Testing Techniques

Functional Testing - type of testing that checks if the software works according to the functional requirements. Basically, what is the software supposed to do.

Types:

User Acceptance Testing (UAT) - final step in the testing process, where the end users or clients test the software to make sure it meets their needs before it’s released to the public. It happens after all the other tests (like functional, integration, and system testing) are done, which means it’s the last chance to find any issues before the software is deployed.

Exploratory Testing - testers explore the software without predefined test cases. Instead of following a strict plan, they interact with the software, trying out different things to see how it behaves.

Sanity Testing – When you add something new (like a feature or a bug fix), it's a test to make sure the new change is functioning as expected.

Ex: Imagine a login system:

· A bug in the password field was fixed

· Now you do sanity testing by:

o Trying to log in with the correct password

o Trying a wrong password

You only test the login feature, not the whole app.


Regression Testing - When you add something new, you test the entire software to see if the new change affects any other part of the system.

Ex: You fix a bug in the login system
